  "local_port": 33164,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can your remove white underarm stains from shirts?",
  "response": "Removing white underarm stains from shirts is a common laundry challenge, but with the right techniques and ingredients, you can effectively eliminate these marks and restore your garments. White underarm stains are typically caused by the buildup of deodorant (especially those containing aluminum compounds) and sweat. Here are several methods you can try:\n\n### **1. Baking Soda Paste**\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- 1 part baking soda\n- 1 part water\n\n**Steps:**\n1. **Make the Paste:** Mix equal parts of baking soda and water to form a thick paste.\n2. **Apply to Stain:** Apply the paste directly to the stained area, ensuring it's well-covered.\n3. **Let It Sit:** Allow the paste to sit on the fabric for at least 30 minutes. For older or more stubborn stains, you can let it sit for a few hours or overnight.\n4. **Scrub Gently:** Using a soft brush or toothbrush, gently scrub the stained area to help lift the residue.\n5. **Wash Normally:** Launder the shirt as you normally would, following the care label instructions.\n\n### **2. White Vinegar Solution**\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- White vinegar\n- Water\n\n**Steps:**\n1. **Prepare the Solution:** Mix one part white vinegar with one part water.\n2. **Soak the Stain:** Submerge the stained area in the solution and let it soak for at least 30 minutes. For tougher stains, soaking overnight can be more effective.\n3. **Scrub If Needed:** Gently scrub the area with a soft brush to aid in stain removal.\n4. **Wash as Usual:** Launder the shirt normally after treating the stain.\n\n### **3. Hydrogen Peroxide and Baking Soda**\n\n**Note:** This method is suitable for white or colorfast fabrics. Always test on a hidden area first to ensure it doesn\u2019t cause discoloration.\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- 3% hydrogen peroxide\n- 1 tablespoon baking soda\n- 1 teaspoon liquid dish soap\n\n**Steps:**\n1. **Mix Ingredients:** In a small bowl, combine hydrogen peroxide, baking soda, and liquid dish soap.\n2. **Apply to Stain:** Pour or apply the mixture directly onto the stained area.\n3. **Let It Sit:** Allow the solution to sit for about an hour to penetrate and break down the stain.\n4. **Scrub Gently:** Use a soft brush to gently scrub the fabric.\n5. **Rinse and Wash:** Rinse thoroughly with cold water and then launder the shirt as usual.\n\n### **4. Aspirin Treatment**\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- 2-3 uncoated aspirin tablets\n- Water\n\n**Steps:**\n1. **Crush Aspirin:** Crush the aspirin tablets into a fine powder.\n2. **Create a Solution:** Dissolve the crushed aspirin in two tablespoons of warm water.\n3. **Apply to Stain:** Spread the solution over the stained area.\n4. **Let It Sit:** Allow it to sit for several hours or overnight.\n5. **Rinse and Wash:** Rinse with cold water and wash the shirt as usual.\n\n### **5. Lemon Juice and Salt**\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- Lemon juice\n- Table salt\n\n**Steps:**\n1. **Apply Lemon Juice:** Squeeze fresh lemon juice onto the stained area.\n2. **Sprinkle Salt:** Sprinkle table salt over the lemon juice.\n3. **Rub the Fabric:** Gently rub the fabric together to work the mixture into the stain.\n4. **Sun Dry:** Lay the shirt in the sun to enhance the bleaching effect of the lemon juice.\n5. **Wash Normally:** After drying, wash the shirt as you usually would.\n\n### **Preventive Tips to Avoid Future Stains**\n\n- **Switch Deodorants:** Opt for aluminum-free deodorants to reduce the likelihood of white residue buildup.\n- **Let Deodorant Dry:** Apply deodorant and allow it to dry completely before putting on your shirt.\n- **Wash Shirts Promptly:** Don't let sweaty shirts sit for extended periods before washing.\n- **Use a Stain Repellent:** Consider treating clothing with a stain repellent spray to provide an extra layer of protection.\n\n### **Additional Tips**\n\n- **Always Check Care Labels:** Before applying any treatment, ensure that the method is suitable for the fabric type by checking the garment's care label.\n- **Test in a Hidden Area:** Especially when using products like hydrogen peroxide or lemon juice, test the solution on an inconspicuous area of the fabric to ensure it doesn't cause damage or discoloration.\n- **Avoid Heat on Stains:** Don't dry the shirt in a dryer until you're sure the stain is gone, as heat can set the stain permanently.\n\nBy following these methods, you should be able to effectively remove white underarm stains from your shirts and keep them looking fresh and clean.",
